<TITLE> Dhaka stocks dip on profit-taking </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 7 (bdnews24.con)Dhaka stocks lost nearly one percent as investors booked profit on banks pulling down indices. The DGEN or general index lost 38.85 points or 0.88 percent to finish at 4344.45. The market, however, witnessed a rise of 28 points in the index during the first hour. Meanwhile, the Chittagong Stock Exchange also witnessed falling indices. The selective categories index or CSCX plunged 105.93 points or 1.28 percent following the trend of the prime bourse. It ended on 8138.25. "Banks were on the rise for quite some time, a usual trend in this part of the year. Investors, mostly retailers, offloaded the bank shares for profit," said Nasiruddin Chowdhry, who heads Lanka Bangla Securities. Banking sector, which accounts more than 50 percent of the market capitalisation, see higher prices at the yearend. Monday's trading left the market driver, banks, to lose on average by 2.72 percent with mutual funds following. Most of the non-bank financial institutions and insurers, however, maintained a rise while power and energy shares suffered loses. However, analysts termed the market behavior as normal. "It's a normal phenomenon...bank prices were surging for the last two weeks, a profit taking was imminent," Salahuddin Ahmed Khan, a former DSE chief executive told bdnews24.com. He added that there was no reason to worry about the falling indices.
